Import and read the data. Here we will also convert the date to epoch time (# of days since 01/01/1970) so the gam function can read it. We also convert the month variable into numeric decimals. More info about this can be found here. https://fromthebottomoftheheap.net/2014/05/09/modelling-seasonal-data-with-gam/

#reads the file. ASSUMES YOUR DIRECTORY IS SET TO THE FOLDER CONTAINING THIS FILE AND THAT Count_Data.csv IS IN THIS FOLDER.
counts<-read.csv(file="Count Data.csv")
#Ensures that date is viewed as a date format by R
counts$Date <- as.Date(counts$Date,format = "%m/%d/%Y")

elapsed_months <- function(end_date, start_date) {
    ed <- as.POSIXlt(end_date)
    sd <- as.POSIXlt(start_date)
    12 * (ed$year - sd$year) + (ed$mon - sd$mon)
}

counts$Months_Passed <- elapsed_months(counts$Date,"2013-05-22")

#Calculcates a new field called time, used for GAM
counts$time <- as.integer(as.Date(counts$Date, format = "%d/%m/%Y"))
#Converts Habitat to factor
counts$Habitat <- factor(counts$Habitat)
levels(counts$Habitat) <- list(Cobble  = "C", Nostoc = "N", Run = "R")
#Calcualtes Day Of Year which can be used to model seasonality
counts$DOY <- format(counts$Date, "%j")
#calcualtes year
counts$year <- format(counts$Date, "%Y")

Now let’s make a simple model.Because each habitat was sampled multiple times on each date, we will fist summarize by date and habitat. That is, we will calculate the average value for each habitat at each date.

monthly_means<- counts %>%
  group_by(Date,Habitat,Obs,Month,Months_Passed,time,year,COBBLE,NOSTOC,RUN) %>%
  summarize(mean_count=mean(Count),n=n())
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Date', 'Habitat', 'Obs', 'Month', 'Months_Passed', 'time', 'year', 'COBBLE', 'NOSTOC'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
monthly_means$NumDays = monthly_means$time-15847

I also want to include water temperature and pH, so we’ll have to import the water quality data, and then merge it with monthly means.

First, lets import the data. It is also in this folder which means as long as your directory is set, all you need to do is read the filename. We will import it and do all of the manipulation here so it can be reproduced in the future, if needed. The file ‘Daily Temperatures’ has temp and pH data, so we will just call it ‘wq,’ short for ‘water quality’.

#reads the file. ASSUMES YOUR DIRECTORY IS SET TO THE FOLDER CONTAINING THIS FILE AND THAT Daily Temperatures.csv IS IN THIS FOLDER.
wq<-read.csv(file="Daily Temperatures.csv")
#ensure Date is recognized as a date
wq$Date<-as.Date(wq$Date,format = "%m/%d/%Y")
#calcualte the month so we can summarize by month
wq<- wq %>%
  mutate(month = format(Date, "%m"),year = format(Date, "%Y"))
#Now calucalting elapsed months which is equivalent to Months_Passed in the count data.
elapsed_months <- function(end_date, start_date) {
    ed <- as.POSIXlt(end_date)
    sd <- as.POSIXlt(start_date)
    12 * (ed$year - sd$year) + (ed$mon - sd$mon)
    }
wq<-wq %>%
  mutate(monthspassed = elapsed_months(Date,"2005-01-01"))
wq$month<-as.factor(wq$month)
#Now merge to monthly_means. We need to create a date format that is only month-year for the merge to work
monthly_means$mergedate = format(as.Date(monthly_means$Date), "%Y-%m")

monthwq<-wq %>%
  select(monthspassed,year,month,Daily.Temp,pH,) %>%
  group_by(year,month,monthspassed) %>%
  summarize(n= n(),
            avgtemp = mean(Daily.Temp),
            sdtemp=sd(Daily.Temp),
            maxtemps=max(Daily.Temp),
            avgpH=mean(pH),
            sdpH=sd(pH))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'year', 'month'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
monthwq$date <- as.Date(with(monthwq, paste(year, month, "15",sep="-")), "%Y-%m-%d")

monthwq$mergedate = format(as.Date(monthwq$date), "%Y-%m")
datum <- merge(monthly_means,monthwq,by ="mergedate")
#Since I already built models using pH and temp, I'll create colmns using these names isntead of avgtemp and avgpH. I don't want to rename them because 1. rename() is being finicky, 2. I also have models using the old names.)
datum$pH<-datum$avgpH
datum$temp<-datum$avgtemp

While we are at it, let’s export these data so we can submit them with the publication. They will be exported to whatever folder your deirectory is set to.

monthwq$date2<-format(monthwq$date,format = "%m/%d/%Y")
write.csv(monthwq, "WQ.csv")

Now we are ready to start selecting terms for our model. We want to determine how mean counts change over time, but we also have water temperature and pH data. Both of these have also probably changed over time, so including all three in the model will lead to issues of concurvity (think of concurvity as analogous to collinearity - except here we have a non-linear response curve.)

Because the data are time series, we can probably also expect the data to be autocorrelated. We can account for this with a correlaion term. To start with, lets try a first order autoregressive term. We can examine ACF and PACF plots after the model is made to determine if we need to change the correlation term.

We will use a backwards elimination process, minimizing AIC and removing non significant terms.

ctrl <- list(niterEM = 0, msVerbose = FALSE, optimMethod="L-BFGS-B")
#fist include all terms, except pH(it isn't compatible with corARMA by year, becasue there aren't enought unique values)

m1 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat)+s(avgtemp)+s(avgpH)+s(Month, bs = "cc", k =12)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 1),
            control = ctrl)
summary(m1$gam)

Month, which I included to address seasonality is not significant. Neither are avgtemp or avgpH. We can also see there is concurvity. Since concurvitry can bias estimates, lets address that before dealing with month. I suspect both pH and temp cause concurvity with time, because they both changed over time. pH and Temp are also often related in aquatic systems. In reality, all of them probably contribute to Pygmy Sculpin counts, but for an accurate model we on;y want to include the term that explains the most variation. We’ll create a new model without avgtemp (because it is the lease significant) and then compare it with the original model.

m2 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=12)+s(avgpH)+s(Month, bs = "cc", k =12)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 1),
            control = ctrl)

Now we will put avgtemp back in, and remove avgpH, then we will put avgpH back in and remove month. We will then use AIC tro comapre all of these models. Most likely, the model without acgtemp will be the best, becasue avg temp was least significant.

#pH removed, temp remians.
m3 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=20)+s(avgtemp)+s(Month, bs = "cc", k =12)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 1),
            control = ctrl)

#month removed, temp and pH remain.
m4 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=20)+s(avgtemp)+s(avgpH)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 1),
            control = ctrl)

#Now a quick comparison of AIC will tell us which model is among these 4 is best.
anova(m1$lme,m2$lme,m3$lme,m4$lme)

We still have two terms that are not significant, and concurvity. Let’s keep working backwards. Again, we will create new models, each with one of the non-significant terms removed, then we will compare them all with AIC.

#remove months
m5 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=12)+s(avgpH)+Habitat,

#remove avgpH
m6 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=12)+s(Month, bs = "cc", k =12)+Habitat,

There appears to be some autocorrelation, but otherwise the residuals look good. We’ll see if the autocorrelation is significant next. Also, note that on the gam check, p-values are low but k is not close to edf. Based on the residuals, I think this model will work, as long as the autocorrelation is not significant. So, let’s look.

layout(matrix(1:2, ncol = 2))
acf(resid(m7$gam), lag.max = 36, main = "ACF")
pacf(resid(m7$gam), lag.max = 36, main = "pACF")

layout(1)

The blue lines represent significance thresholds. Overall, the model does not have much significant autocorrelation, but a second order autocorrelation term may be warranted.

m8 <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(Months_Passed, by = Habitat,k=12)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 2),
            control = ctrl)
anova(m7$lme,m8$lme)

The second autocorrelation term made the model worse. Given the large sample size, and that the only lags 2 and 6 have very mild, significant autocorrelation, I am comfortable with this model. I suggest we see that the reviewers think. In the mean time, let’s plot the model.

First the response curves.

plot(m7$gam)

It looks like there is a slight decrease in all habitats, but cobble had the most severe decrease.

Let’s make the plot nicer. Also note that the predictions from the model will mirror the response curves, becasue only one term, months_passed (time), was significant. Normally, the predictions for GAMS is the sum off all response curves.

I used months passed to measure time, but that doesn’t graph as neatly. So, I’ll use the same model, but with days as the units for the x-axis.

m7pred <- gamm(mean_count ~ s(time, by = Habitat)+Habitat,
            data = datum, correlation = corARMA(form = ~ 1|year.x, p = 1),
            control = ctrl)

predictCount <- predict_gam(m7pred$gam)
#Convert epoch time to date for graphing
predictCount$date <- as.Date(predictCount$time,origin = "1970-01-01")

Note - to appease the reviewers, I’ve added this to scale_x_date. limits = as.Date(c(‘2013-01-01’,‘2019-01-01’)). I think it looks better without because it had less white space at low values of x.
